1. Process ID (PID)
Unique identification number of the process.

Example:
Process numbers assigned in systems like Linux or Microsoft Windows.

2. Process State
Stores the current state:
New
Ready
Running
Waiting
Terminated

3. Program Counter
Stores the address of the next instruction to be executed.

4. CPU Registers
Stores register values like:
Accumulator
Index registers
Stack pointer

5. CPU Scheduling Information
Contains scheduling data such as:
Priority
Queue pointers
Scheduling parameters

6. Memory Management Information
Contains memory-related data:
Base register
Limit register
Page tables
Segment tables

7. Accounting Information
Stores:
CPU usage time
Process number
Time limits
User ID

8. I/O Status Information
Contains:
Allocated devices
Open files list
I/O request status
